h what encourages and what blocks capitalism. In On Capitalism leading economists, sociologists, and political scientists develop ideas and insights into the dynamic of capitalism as a global economic order. Unlike studies that focus only on localized descriptions of what has made capitalism function in a specific place, these essays examine the general mechanisms that account for dynamic or rational capitalism. As each chapter shows, the mechanisms motivating and facilitating today's global capitalism are not rooted in the materialist domain of incremental capital accumulation, but in the realm of ideas and institutional structures. Taken as a whole, these essays offer a rich account of the interconnectedness of the economic, political, and religious institutions of modern capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh1 aBarro, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarruthers, Bruce G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Robert H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranovetter, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalliday, Terence C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardin, Russell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJepperson, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh, Barnaby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCleary, Rachel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNee, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNee, Victo